%N A392335 a(n) is the product of primes p such that n is not the divisor d with largest abundancy among proper divisors of p*n (where d is the least such divisor if there is more than one).
%C A392335 This sequence is found from A395192. Relating it to that sequence, a(n) is the product of primes p such that A395192(p*n) != n. For all except finitely many primes p, n is the least proper divisor of p*n with the largest abundancy, i.e. A395192(p*n) = n.
%C A392335 See A395192 for more information.
%F A392335 a(n) = A007947(A137825(m)/n), where m = min({k : n|A137825(k)}).
%e A392335 Recall that A395192(n) is the least k with the largest abundancy where k is a proper divisor of n and the abundancy of k is sigma(k)/k, where sigma is the sum of divisors function, A000203.
%e A392335 a(4) = 15. The proper divisor of 4*3 = 12 with largest abundancy is 6 with abundancy sigma(6)/6 12/6 = 2. That is a larger abundancy than sigma(4)/4 = 7/4 = 1.75 so 3 | a(4). The proper divisor of 4*5 with largest abundancy is 10 with sigma(10)/10 = 1.8 so 5 | a(4). 2 doesn't divide a(4) as 4 is the proper divisor of 4*2 with largest abundancy. For all primes > 7 the proper divisor with largest abundancy is 4 with sigma(4)/4 = 1.75. So a(4) = lcm(3, 5) = 15.
%o A392335 (PARI) a(n) = {if(n==1, return(1)); my(f = factor(n), res = 1); forprime(p = 2, oo, if(A395192(n*p) != n, res*=p, if(p > f[#f~, 1], return(res))))}
%o A392335 A395192(n) = {my(f = factor(n), r = 0, res = 0); forstep(i = #f~, 1, -1, c = sigma(n/f[i,1])/(n/f[i,1]); if(c > r, r = c; res = n/f[i,1])); res}
%Y A392335 Cf. A000203, A007947, A395192.
%Y A392335 Positions of 1's: A137825.
%K A392335 nonn,new
